intended_learning_outcomes_of_course.value:
By the end of this course, students will be able to: 
Use current operating system terminology in correctly explaining the functions of an OS;
Relate operating system functions to computer hardware;
Describe the mechanisms of interrupts, context switching and address translation;
Describe the relation of operating system functions to language run-time systems;
Explain the significance of concurrency in operating system design;
Demonstrate an understanding of the semantics of operating system functions, including scheduling and memory management, by being able to describe their functioning;
Implement simple operating system components and basic algorithms (CPU scheduling, deadlock detection and avoidance algorithms);
Critique designs and implementations of OS components, eg the Unix file system;
Illustrate the influence of operating system functions on application behaviour;
Compare and contrast alternative approaches to hardware components such as the CPU and bus;
Engineer medium-sized (multi-file) software components for integration into larger C and/or Java programs.
